com.netcracker.edu.java.tasks

Interface ComplexNumber

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable<ComplexNumber>

    public interface ComplexNumber
extends java.lang.Comparable<ComplexNumber>, java.lang.Cloneable
    GOALS
    • To learn OOP basics: basic principles of writing a class, getters/setters, this keyword.
    • To get familiar with some methods of Object and with Comparable interface.
    • To be able to use some java.lang and java.itil API: String, Double, Arrays.

    TASK
    Implement a class storing a single complex number with basic mathematical operations on it.
    Instances of the class must be comparable, cloneable and representable as String (in the common format).

    REQUIREMENTS

    • The complex number consists of two components: real part (re) and imaginary part (im). They should be stored as private fields (members of the class) of type double or Double. After instantiation of the number with default constructor both re and im must be equal to 0.
    • Every math operation on the number (add, negate, multiply methods) should change the state of this object not creating a new object (this requirement is intended to save memory and to lower calculation time). For a caller's convenience, all these methods (math operations) return this object itself.
    • The common requirement for any task (to check it online) is to declare your class as follows:
      public class ComplexNumberImpl implements ComplexNumber { }

    NOTES

    • When coded with the methods of this interface, formulas like z = x-y^2 could look like this:
      ComplexNumber z = x.add(y.copy().multiply(y).negate());
      where x, y are objects of type ComplexNumber.
    • The task can be solved without any knowledge of Exceptions, but if you know that topic explicit generation of NumberFormatException in set(String) method is recommended.
    • It's recommended (but not required) to have the following set of constructors:
      public ComplexNumberImpl(double re, double im);
      public ComplexNumberImpl(String value);
      public ComplexNumberImpl(); (this no-argument constructor is required by the checking system).
    • If you don't understand the mathematical meaning of the complex number you can read e.g. Complex Number at Wikipedia.
    • A professional Java implementation of this concept can be found here: Complex in Apache Commons Math.

      • set

        void set(java.lang.String value)
  throws java.lang.NumberFormatException
        Parses the given string value and sets the real and imaginary parts of this number accordingly.
        The string format is "re+imi", where re and im are numbers (floating point or integer) and 'i' is a special symbol denoting imaginary part (if present, it's always the last character in the string).
        Both '+' and '-' symbols can be the first characters of re and im; but '*' symbol is NOT allowed.
        Correct examples: "-5+2i", 1+i", "+4-i", "i", "-3i", "3". Incorrect examples: "1+2*i", "2+2", "j".
        Note: explicit exception generation is an OPTIONAL requirement for this task, but NumberFormatException can be thrown by Double.parseDouble(String)).
        Note: it is not reasonable to use regex while implementing this method: the parsing logic is too complicated.
        Parameters:
        value -
        Throws:
        java.lang.NumberFormatException - if the given string value is incorrect

             throws java.lang.CloneNotSupportedException

      • toString

        java.lang.String toString()
        Returns a string representation of this number, which must be compatible with set(String): for any ComplexNumber x, the code x.set(x.toString()); must not change x.
        For example: 12.5-1.0i or 0.0 or 0.3333333333333333i
        If the imaginary part of the number is 0, only "re" must be returned (where re is the real part).
        If the real part of the number is 0 and the imaginary part is not 0, "imi" must be returned (where im is the imaginary part).
        Both re and im must be converted to string "as is" - without truncation of last digits, i.e. the number of characters in their string representation is not limited (it is determined by Double.toString(double)).
        Overrides:
        toString in class java.lang.Object
        See Also:
        Object.toString()

      • compareTo

        int compareTo(ComplexNumber other)
        Compares this number with the other number by the absolute values of the numbers: x < y if and only if |x| < |y| where |x| denotes absolute value (modulus) of x.
        Can also compare the square of the absolute value which is defined as the sum of the real part squared and the imaginary part squared: |re+imi|^2 = re^2 + im^2.
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<ComplexNumber>
        Parameters:
        other - the object to be compared with this object.
        Returns:
        a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as this object is less than, equal to, or greater than the given object.
        See Also:
        Comparable.compareTo(Object)

      • sort

        void sort(ComplexNumber[] array)
        Sorts the given array in ascending order according to the comparison rule defined in compareTo(ComplexNumber).
        It's strongly recommended to use Arrays utility class here (and do not transform the given array to a double[] array).
        Note: this method could be static: it does not use this instance of the ComplexNumber. Nevertheless, it is not static because static methods can't be overridden.
        Parameters:
        array - an array to sort

      • multiply

        ComplexNumber multiply(ComplexNumber arg2)
        Multiplies this number by the given complex number arg2. If this number is a+bi and arg2 is c+di then the result of their multiplication is (a*c-b*d)+(b*c+a*d)i
        The method should work correctly even if arg2==this.
        Parameters:
        arg2 - the second operand of the operation
        Returns:
        this number (the result of multiplication)
